# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abkhazian-dze
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:abkhazian-dze/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:abkhazian-dze/abkhazian-dze] It is also used in a 2007 alphabet for the Uilta language, where it represents a voiced postalveolar affricate [dʒ], as in the ⟨j⟩ in ***j**am*.
[src:abkhazian-dze/abkhazian-dze] It was also used in one 1937 proposal (not adopted) for the Karelian language.
[src:abkhazian-dze/abkhazian-dze] The letter is often homoglyphic with the Latin letter Ezh ⟨Ʒ ʒ⟩, but in some fonts the uppercase form of the Abkhazian Dze has no descender or has a shortened tail.
[src:abkhazian-dze/abkhazian-dze] This letter is equivalent to the more common Cyrillic Dze, differing only in shape.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] It has religious and cultural significance in many societies.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] The use of three lines to denote the number 3 occurred in many writing systems, including some (like Roman and Chinese numerals) that are still in use.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] That was also the original representation of 3 in the Brahmic (Indian) numerical notation, its earliest forms aligned vertically.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] However, during the Gupta Empire, the sign was modified by the addition of a curve on each line.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] The Nāgarī script rotated the lines clockwise, so they appeared horizontally, and ended each line with a short downward stroke on the right.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] In cursive script, the three strokes were eventually connected to form a symbol resembling a ⟨3⟩ with an additional stroke at the bottom: **३**.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] The Indian digits spread to the Caliphate in the 9th century.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] The bottom stroke was dropped around the 10th century in the western parts of the Caliphate, such as the Maghreb and Al-Andalus, when a distinct variant ("Western Arabic") of the digit symbols developed, including modern Western 3.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] In contrast, the Eastern Arabs retained and enlarged that stroke, rotating the digit once more to yield the modern ("Eastern") Arabic digit "**٣**".
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] In most modern Western typefaces, the digit 3, like the other decimal digits, has the height of a capital letter, and sits on the baseline.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] In typefaces with text figures, on the other hand, the glyph usually has the height of a lowercase letter "x" and a descender: "".
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] In some French text-figure typefaces, though, it has an ascender instead of a descender.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] A common graphic variant of the digit three has a flat top, similar to the letter Ʒ (ezh).
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] This form, sometimes called a **banker's 3**, can stop a forger from turning the 3 into an 8.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] It is found on UPC-A barcodes and standard 52-card decks.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] A natural number is divisible by 3 if the sum of its digits in base 10 is also divisible by 3.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] This known as the divisibility rule of 3.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] Because of this, the reverse of any number that is divisible by three (or indeed, any permutation of its digits) is also divisible by three.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] This divisibility rule works in any positional numeral system whose base divided by three leaves a remainder of one (bases 4, 7, 10, etc.).
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] 3 is the second smallest prime number and the first odd prime number.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] It is a twin prime with 5, and a cousin prime with 7.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] It is the smallest non-self-intersecting polygon and the only polygon not to have proper diagonals.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] When doing quick estimates, 3 is a rough approximation of π, 3.1415..., and a very rough approximation of *e*, 2.71828...
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] It is also the first of five known Fermat primes.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] It is the second Fibonacci prime (and the second Lucas prime), the second Sophie Germain prime, and the second factorial prime.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] 3 is the second and only prime triangular number, and Carl Friedrich Gauss proved that every integer is the sum of at most three triangular numbers.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] Three is the only prime which is one less than a perfect square.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] Any other number which is $n^{2}$ − 1 for some integer n is not prime, since it is ( n − 1)( n + 1).
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] This is true for 3 as well (with n = 2), but in this case the smaller factor is 1.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] If n is greater than 2, both n − 1 and n + 1 are greater than 1 so their product is not prime.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] The integers modulo 3 form the finite field $\mathbb {F} _{3}$ , the smallest finite field of odd characteristic.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] In algebraic geometry, characteristic 3 is one of the small characteristics in which standard formulas may require separate treatment; for example, elliptic curves in characteristics 2 and 3 do not always admit short Weierstrass equations of the form $y^{2}=x^{3}+Ax+B$ .
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] There is some evidence to suggest that early man may have used counting systems which consisted of "One, Two, Three" and thereafter "Many" to describe counting limits.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] Early peoples had a word to describe the quantities of one, two, and three, but any quantity beyond was simply denoted as "Many".
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] This is most likely based on the prevalence of this phenomenon among people in such disparate regions as the deep Amazon and Borneo jungles, where Western civilization's explorers have historical records of their first encounters with these indigenous people.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] Three non-collinear points determine a unique plane in a three dimensional affine space, and a unique circle in a Euclidean plane.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] An object has rotational symmetry of order 3 if it is unchanged by a rotation of one third of a full turn, or 120 degrees.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] The triangle, a polygon with three edges and three vertices, is the most stable physical shape.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] For this reason it is widely utilized in construction, engineering and design.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] Three is the symbolic representation for Mu, Augustus Le Plongeon's and James Churchward's lost continent.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] Many world religions contain triple deities or concepts of trinity, including the Hindu Trimurti and Tridevi, the Triglav (lit.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] 'Three-headed one'), the chief god of the Slavs, the three Jewels of Buddhism, the three Pure Ones of Taoism, the Christian Trinity, the Greek goddess Hecate and the Triple Goddess of Wicca.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] Pythagoras and the Pythagorean school highlighted that the number 3, which they called *triad*, is the only number to equal the sum of all the terms below it, and the only number whose sum with those below equals the product of them and itself.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] The phrase "Third time's the charm" refers to the superstition that after two failures in any endeavor, a third attempt is more likely to succeed.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] However, some superstitions say the opposite, stating that luck, especially bad luck, is often said to "come in threes".
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] One such superstition, called "Three on a Match", says that it is unlucky to be the third person to light a cigarette from the same match or lighter.
[src:abkhazian-dze/page] This superstition is sometimes asserted to have originated among soldiers in the trenches of the First World War when a sniper might see the first light, take aim on the second and fire on the third.
